<!-- Before You Buy Section -->
<section id="before-you-buy">
    <h2>Before You Buy: Check Your Bed Frame</h2>

    <p>Before ordering a new mattress, there are a few things you need to check ‚Äî especially if you have an antique bed or an RV.</p>

    <h3>For Antique Bed Owners</h3>

    <p>Antique bed frames are often very sturdy and well-made. But after 80-100+ years, things can break down. <strong>A new mattress will have the same problems as your old one if the support underneath isn't solid.</strong></p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Check your box spring (if you have one):</strong> Run your hand along the entire surface. Feel for any metal or wood that is bent, cracked, or broken. Broken internal components cause uneven support, leading to sagging and body impressions in your new mattress.</li>
        <li><strong>Check your bed frame support rails:</strong> The rails that support your mattress and box spring can come loose over time. If the support rails aren't screwed in tight and completely solid, the mattress will sag.</li>
        <li><strong>Check for any loose or broken components:</strong> Go over the entire frame. Tighten any loose screws. Replace any broken slats.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>For Antique Beds with Notched Corners</h3>

    <p>Some antique beds have bedposts that require notched corners on the mattress. You have two options:</p>

    <p><strong>Option 1: Order a custom notched mattress</strong> ‚Äî Companies like Mattress Insider can make mattresses with notched corners cut to your exact specifications.</p>

    <p><strong>Option 2: Buy an all-foam mattress and let the corners squish</strong> ‚Äî Purchase an all-foam mattress (like the Dreamfoam Essential or PlushBeds Latex) and simply let the corners compress around the bedposts. Foam is flexible ‚Äî it bends around obstacles without damaging the mattress. We've seen this work perfectly in many homes.</p>

    <h3>For RV Owners</h3>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Check your clearance:</strong> Before ordering, measure the depth/height that fits in your RV. Some RV beds are under a folding table, counter, or cabinet that limits how thick your mattress can be.</li>
        <li><strong>Check for odd cutouts:</strong> Some 3/4 RV beds have a slight notch or rounded edge. If the custom edge isn't too prominent, you can often purchase an all-foam mattress and let the foam bend around the notch.</li>
        <li><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Many RV owners purchase a memory foam or latex mattress and use a turkey carving knife to cut the edge out themselves. Foam cuts easily.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Temperature Note for RV Owners</h3>

    <p>Memory foam is temperature-sensitive:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Cold temperatures:</strong> Memory foam feels firmer as it hardens</li>
        <li><strong>Warm temperatures:</strong> Memory foam feels softer and more "mushy"</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Memory foam is still great for RVs, but understand that the feel will change in different climates. If you want consistent firmness regardless of temperature, consider latex or a hybrid option instead.</p>
</section>

